   09-06-2012 11:19 AM

   Do you have any paperwork from his doctor telling the school what to do
   when he has high numbers?  If they aren't following it, then you have a
   case.  If you don't have a detailed Medical Management Plan, get one
   asap!  In it, the doctor (with your help) can lay out how your son is
   to be treated for highs, lows, etc..  You'll probably find the nurse
   with the attitude that if it isn't in his medical plan, then she can't
   do it as she can only follow doctor's orders.(the plan)   And you might
   want to look into getting a 504 plan in place for him also.  Those are
   harder to get as alot of schools fight the kids having one even though
   they're entittled to one per the Americans with Disabilities Act.
   Diabetes is considered a disability in how it effects kids and
   schoolwork.   It's just so many school are so not on board with
   complying with having one for their students with D.







   Mother of Courtney, Dx'd Type 1 in 2006 at age 14.
   Self: Dx'd "Pre"-Diabetic 8/8/14 *and we all know what that means*
