   09-06-2012 11:25 AM

   Hi I can't remember how old your son is or if he is on a pump or
   injections.  If he went to check his blood sugar before lunch and it
   was high, no ketones and he felt ok, the nurse should have had him
   bolus or cover for lunch and add correction and go eat and drink.  have
   him come back and check again in 2 hours.  Staying in the office is not
   going to accomplish anything.  If he felt crummy and ketones were
   present, then yes he probably needed to come home.  the first couple
   weeks of school are awful for trying to get blood sugar back on track.
   there is the stress of school, new eating and sleeping patterns,
   allergy season, you name it.  Poking the kid's finger every 15 or 20
   minutes is not going to accomplish anything for a high.  We really
   struggled with this in middle school.  our son was being held in the
   office off and on all day.  His grades suffered, he was stressed out
   and his teachers were no help.  We thought the nurse communicated to
   staff, but that was not happeneing.  Finally, unless it was a low or he
   felt crummy, we stopped blood sugar checks other than lunch.  By that
   time, his school day had become all about diabetes and not school.  We
   put the focus back on communicating with his teachers and not the
   nurse.  Now, he is 17.  Some days are good and some are not but school,
   sports etc do not stop over it.  Good luck and let us know how it turns
   out.























   G 18 diagnosed 3/22/08
